"I gotta say it's fun having you here" … "really?" … "no"

False advertising, honestly...

Comment:
*****
You say "social conditioning" as if it's a bad thing, while it's the most natural thing in the world. We as people live in societies, and societies change over the years and centuries. Call it "values", "moral concepts" or "social conditioning", it's all the same thing.
No big evil world conspiracy behind it, no femnazis, no PC-world police, just societies changing and growing up.

And FYI, I am white, not a comic book reader and wouldn't know about some "cannon". As far as I know there have been a multiple film versions of Batman out there (to give an example), with different origin stories of the Dark Knight himself, of the Joker, of Catwoman etc. And has there been outrage at some of the decisions by fanboys?...sure (having the Joker kill Bruce Wayne's parents in the first Tim Burton film, the whole Ben Affleck thing, and remember, the fanboys were quite outspoken against Heath Ledger in the beginning too)...I know that the Avengers movies are very different than the comics, I know there are multiple "universes" or stories of the X-Men in the comics and so on...(so IS there even a cannon for comic book characters? Sure doesn't look like it)

But I am sorry, when it's comes to the oppression of an actor playing a part of a FICTIONAL character just because of the color of is skin...that's just a big bloody line right there. Let's face it, it's not like they asked Samuel L. Jackson to play Lincoln or something, they just made a film based on a comic book! If you think that's enough reason to be a racist, then I have to assume your comic books are like scripure to you, concluding you are as big a nutcase/fundamentalist/zealot as any other religious person out there.

And furthermore, Hollywood does re-invent, re-tell and re-cast stories all the time, but that one black guy is such problem? Even when he is one the best actors of his generation??

Makes no sense at all!

Secondly, it would be a different story changing a black superhero to a white one. Heterosexual, white men have the loudest voice (read: representation) in our society. Taking one away does not affect the commonality of this voice. However, doing so to an African American character would because there are fewer. It's a matter of proportion.

Comment: Here's the issue with changing the race of the characters: Fantastic four has been around for about 50 years. The characters were known as the way they were portrayed through the comics. Call it whatever you will, but these characters were white. Changing the race of certain characters in certain tales does a lot to the actual story. What if we changed Tom Sawyer to a black guy? How about if we switched roles in Men in Black? The issue isn't about "Racial Equality" or how the "Oh-so-evil white people are closed minded to change," the issue is that these are familiar territories, territories that we have grown up with and loved, and these changes warp the way the world was envisioned by its creators. It's not about the actor being black, he's a good actor, and he can definitely have significant roles, but the Human Torch simply isn't black. It's not what we grew up with, it's not how the characters were portrayed in the marvel universe from countless games, comics, and even to the movies before this. On top of the race issue, comics have come to change the sexuality of comic book heroes. There is so much room for more comic book heroes to be made of different races without the need of changing the races of existing comic book heroes.

Comment:
"It's clobberin' time!" 

But....... is it, though?

After successfully designing a telelporting device, Reed Richards is recruited out of high school to work for a group of scientists trying to teleport to another dimension. After getting to this other dimension, Reed, Johnny Storm, Susan Storm, Ben Grimm and Victor Von Doom are mutated by the cosmic energies of the dimension and given superhuman abilities.

It's The Fantastic Four... Fox's SECOND crack at this franchise after letting Tim Story waste everyone's time with it, too. 

Directed by Josh Trank who was an ideal choice to reboot FF after making such a good original superhero movie with Chronicle, which was packed with good ideas.... and none of them show up here.

Apparently Trank says Fox ruined his movie and that his original idea was to turn FF into a sort of body horror movie, which sounds great and there's like.... inklings of this in the movie when it all breaks back in the other dimension and everyone wakes up after and it's kinda freaky. I got a SLIGHT tough of District 9's horrific take on an action movie. But whatver Trank's idea for this movie was... the end product is a complete zilch.

Fanastic Four in the comics is a witty sci-fi adventure story with our heroes traversing the world and the cosmos fighting all kinds of villains and monsters...

This movie.... it's about 1 hour and 17 minutes in before we get what I could even come close to describing as an action scene, when Doctor Doom makes his first powered appearance. And there is not one laugh or even grin-worthy moment in the entire film. I could not believe how humor-free this movie was. One thing about ALL Marvel comics is their decent sense of humor in every book...... so yeah let's make a movie out of FF where the aim seems to be to make the audience just sit there for 90 minutes and not have any fun.

All the actors are so stiff aside from Michael B Jordan who's the closest anyone comes to looking like they're having fun acting in this goddamned movie. 

It's halfway through the movie when the sci-fi element kicks in and we get to the other dimension... and then another half hour before anything exciting happens again...... and then it's over. This movie cost over 150 million 

I'm not the slightest bit confused as to why this movie didn't click with audiences on any level whatsoever. 

This movie makes the 2005 and 2007 Fantastic Four movies look like Infinity War and Endgame.

It's rare to watch a comic book movie and watch it just fail on every single imaginable level and just go down in flames.

Nothing fantastic about this, in fact I've already forgotten it.

Comment:
there was a time where I used to defend this movie a little bit. 
I never said it was great film, but I also never saw it as the WORST film ever made. 
and for a while I was convinced that the reason I defended it was because I did enjoy little more than most other folks. 

However, I have come to realize,... that actually wasn't true. 
to tell you the truth, the Real Reason I defended this movie back then was NOT because I actually enjoyed it...but more because... I felt Sorry for it. 

like I knew that at least 80% of the problems weren't the film's own fault. 
it's just another one of those poor films that was almost a good movie, but got fucked up by a studio that had no idea what they actually wanted. 
and in the end, became a forgettable, boring piece of mid that insured people to never trust Fox with the F4 property ever again😔

so while I do agree now that it's Not Good, I STILL feel bad for it. when I watch I can just tell that there was a decent movie somewhere and it got buried by shitty changes ordered by the studio. it's also sad that Josh himself isn't even open to seeing the original he wanted to be out there be seen by anyone.

Cool and rowdy teenager Johnny Storm becomes Human Torch, able to control, project fire, transform to his fiery form, throws fireballs and flying ability, while his older sister Susan becomes the Invisible Woman, who can turn invisible and create force fields to protect herself and her teammates or to attack her enemies. Comment:
The only thing that was worth from this movie was the design of "thing". Everything else was pure garbage.
1) Why did you use kid actors to play the roles? Reed had grey hair in comics and Ben was close to his age. Sue and Johnny were the young ones.
2) Making Johnny Storm black. Sure let’s make Johnny Storm black... Brilliant idea! Congrats to the guy who thought about it!!
3) They got their powers by traveling to space, not by switching dimensions
Finally This stupid Political correctness ruined many movies for no real reason!
Same thing to the latest spiderman movies. I cant even begin with that...
You want a black hero? Find an existing or create a new one! Why would anyone be offended by the fact that all the team are white? I wonder why they didn't shoot it with all of them as women characters.
Fantastic four were my favorite superheroes and somehow they managed to ruin it for me.
You have comic material to make this work... Just use it and stop making stupid modifications to it!
